<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

<div class="space-y-6">
<div>
<h3>What makes Champagne different from other sparkling wines?</h3>
<p>Champagne must come from the Champagne region of France and follow strict production methods including méthode champenoise. The unique terroir, climate, and traditional techniques create Champagne's distinctive flavor profile and fine bubble structure that other sparkling wines cannot replicate.</p>
</div>

<div>
<h3>How long can you store Champagne before it goes bad?</h3>
<p>Non-vintage Champagne stays fresh for 3-4 years from purchase when stored properly. Vintage Champagne can age gracefully for 10-20 years or more. Once opened, consume within 1-3 days using a proper Champagne stopper to maintain carbonation and prevent oxidation.</p>
</div>

<div>
<h3>Why is Champagne so expensive compared to other wines?</h3>
<p>The complex méthode champenoise requires two fermentations, extended aging on lees, and labor-intensive riddling and disgorging processes. Limited vineyard area, strict quality controls, and high demand for this prestigious wine category all contribute to premium pricing.</p>
</div>

<div>
<h3>Can you cook with Champagne wine?</h3>
<p>Yes, Champagne works excellently in cooking, particularly for sauces, risottos, and poaching liquids. The acidity and bubbles enhance flavors, though the carbonation dissipates during cooking. Use reasonably priced bottles rather than expensive vintage Champagnes for culinary purposes.</p>
</div>

<div>
<h3>What's the difference between Brut and Extra Brut Champagne?</h3>
<p>Brut contains 6-12 grams of residual sugar per liter, offering balanced dryness with slight sweetness. Extra Brut contains 0-6 grams per liter, creating a more austere, bone-dry style that emphasizes the wine's natural acidity and mineral character.</p>
</div>

<div>
<h3>Should beginners start with non-vintage or vintage Champagne?</h3>
<p>Beginners should start with non-vintage Champagne from reputable houses. These wines offer consistent house style, approachable flavors, and better value. Once familiar with different styles, you can explore vintage Champagnes and grower producers for more complex expressions.</p>
</div>

<div>
<h3>How do you tell if Champagne has gone flat or spoiled?</h3>
<p>Spoiled Champagne lacks carbonation, smells off (vinegar-like or musty), or tastes flat and oxidized. Fresh Champagne should have persistent bubbles, clean aromas, and bright acidity. Properly stored bottles rarely spoil, but improper storage or age can cause deterioration.</p>
</div>

<div>
<h3>What glassware works best for serving Champagne?</h3>
<p>Flute glasses preserve carbonation and concentrate aromatics for most Champagnes. However, wider bowls or white wine glasses work better for complex vintage Champagnes, allowing more surface area for aroma development. Avoid coupe glasses as they cause rapid bubble loss.</p>
